identificationRemarks: "oso de anteojos" las plantas en roseta de segundo plano son del género *Speletia* "frailejones" La foto es muy interesante porque muestra que este animal por excelencia herbívoro, en este sitio se está alimentando de los brotes tiernos de *Speletia*, como se puede ver en el suelo las plantas totalmente desmembradas. Al parecer las plantas arrosetadas son su dieta preferida, ya que en otros sitios donde no hay Speletias, como en el sur de Ecuador consume Bromeliáceas de la misma manera.

occurrenceRemarks: Nombre científico: Tremarctos ornatus Es mayormente herbívoro, pero puede ser carnívoro ocasionalmente. Es es la única especie de oso nativa a Suramérica que sigue viva. Al momento de la observación se veía al oso a gran altura, por eso la foto sale a distancia y el clima estaba templado un poco más frío. Solamente había uno que estaba caminando de manera calmada.

name: Tremarctos ornatus (F.G.Cuvier, 1825)
occurrenceRemarks: At base of palm, observed this bear sliding down the palm with José Castaño, of Jardin. We searched the area by scanning from the road for several hours after reports of bears observed (and photographed) in the area by bird guides. The bear was feeding at the tops of wax palms. Many broken palm tops were observed, totaling approx. 30 palms. The palm in the photo shows a typical broken top. A regrettably poor photo.

occurrenceRemarks: Yes really. Seen on our way out of Manu National Park and a long way down from our viewpoint on the road. Sorry for the lousy photos but my travelling companions and the guide managed much better photos than I did. The view was vertigo-inducing! I dont have an exact location, other than it was seen along the road in and out of the Manu National Park. I've added a 3rd photo, taking by one of my travelling companions, where it's is a little more obvious which animal we were observing.

name: Tremarctos ornatus (F.G.Cuvier, 1825)
occurrenceRemarks: What a Christmas present! We watched this Spectacled Bear near the entrance to Podocarpus National Park for an hour. He was digging and eating puya bromeliads, making loud cracking sounds as he pulled them from the ground. He looked up at us periodically, particularly when our car alarm went off accidentally but seemed totally unconcerned. After an hour, we left him and went further into the park. When we returned, he was still there, about 100 meters downslope from where he'd been previously and he slowly ambled off when he saw us again.
